This project is of three steps involving test assessment, personal bot and entertainment which helps as stepping stone for coping of stressful life this system is used to build for the students as they were easily depressed and has higher depression rate due to higher expectations on the by others and lack of wisdom knowledge to read the situation which can lead the unhealthy relation toward the society 
The First stage consists of psychology questions to understand there understanding toward the nature and there steps of approaching and relations towards society. These understandings were given to the Pre Trained LLM to produce the desired personality to understand the person 
The Second stage is the AI Assistant which is built on the understanding of the test take by the user early the Assistant assist in coping up the stress by speaking up for you and participating actively in your conversation and activity.
The final stage involves in engaging in stress less or coping up stress games to serve the purpose of joyfulness in each individual.
The proposed project aims to develop a comprehensive system to assess an individual’s psychological state through a series of structured assessments and to provide personalized support using an encrypted, pre-trained Large Language Model (LLM). This system will function as a personalized AI companion that promotes healthy coping strategies, monitors behavioural patterns, supports decision-making, and assists individuals during periods of heightened emotional distress or depressive episodes.
II. LITERATURE SURVEY 
In [1], the authors present the growing mental health crisis among students and the rapid advancement of digital technologies have driven significant research into technology-assisted mental healthcare solutions. Abrams (2022) highlights that student mental health has reached a critical stage, with campuses struggling to address increasing levels of anxiety, depression, and stress among students. The study emphasizes the need for scalable, accessible, and innovative approaches beyond traditional counselling services, noting that institutional capacity is often insufficient to meet rising demand. 
   In [2], the authors present Early explorations into human–computer interaction laid the foundation for modern conversational systems. Weizenbaum’s (2008) seminal work on ELIZA demonstrated the feasibility of natural language communication between humans and machines. Although ELIZA relied on simple pattern matching, it illustrated how users could form emotional connections with conversational programs, a phenomenon that remains relevant in today’s chatbot-based mental health interventions.. 
   In [3] the authors present Supporting the urgency of student-focused interventions, the American College Health Association (2022) reports alarming trends in undergraduate mental health through its National College Health Assessment III. The executive summary reveals high prevalence rates of stress, anxiety, and depression, directly impacting academic performance and overall well-being. The report underscores the necessity of preventive and technology-enabled mental health support systems within educational institutions.
